<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-05-02T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-05-02T10:00:00-05:00" n="388" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">863.51 Relief Credits/222: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Edge</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-05-02T16:00:00+01:00">May 2, 1930—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 2—1 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>126. Department’s 93, April 15, 6 p.m., to London. The French Government
                            states that the terms of the letter of April 16 last from Leith-Ross to
                            the Austrian Minister at London express the conditions to which it
                            especially has subordinated its adhesion to the emission of the Austrian
                            loan.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Edge</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
